Long term: as stated above, more interest paying lowers the actuall money to work with. It's like having the bad effect of raising taxes on the economy and having the downside of lowering taxes on your income in the same deal. The actual problem of deficits will be for the next problem. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=simanmistrunner>SimanMistrunner</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 462<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/18/03 9:44:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=332.topic&index=24>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Clinton Speaks</span><hr size=1> We need to make sure we keep two terms separate for this discussion as folks are getting the two confused.  Deficits is the difference between what the Government spends in a given year versus what it brings in for a given year.  To fund deficits, the government needs to issue debt to investors.  The national debt is the aggregate amount of deficits that we have incurred over the years.  We pay interest on the national debt--the recipients of these interest payments are the holders of U.S. treasuries and other debt instruments.<br>
<br>
The national debt of a country should never be looked at in a vacuum--you need to compare it against the size of the overall economy.  The ratio of debt to gdp in the United States is not that high at all, much less than in countries such as Japan.<br>
<br>
While there are costs to debt, you have to weigh the costs against the benefits of incurring more debt.  WIth respect to Bush's tax cuts, I have hard time convincing myself that the benefits derived from the tax cuts outweigh the costs of incurring additional debt to finance those tax cuts.  While I agree that some tax cuts would be helpful, a scaling down of the Bush tax cuts would not get my opposition.<br>
<br>
What are the costs of increased national debt?<br>
<br>
1.  Higher interest coverage--we pay interest on the national debt out of each year's fiscal budget.  The more debt there is, the higher interest payments will be.  That right there is less money than can be spent elsewhere.<br>
<br>
2.  Crowds out private borrowing--there is a dispute among economists to the degree.  The argument goes that as the government issues more debt to investors, that reduces the amount of debt that investors will seek from companies.seeking access to liquidity.<br>
<br>
In many senses, it is a question of what we want to pass onto our children as all debt comes due at some point.  I would rather do everything in our power to limit the growth in our national debt, or even reduce the national debt, as best as we can.  I have no debt in my personal life and it is very freeing.<br>
<br>
This partisan bickering is silly.  Neither party cares about deficit reduction.  There are individuals in each party that do but they are in the minority of their respective parties.  Who are we trying to kid.  Debt reduction is not a priority among Republican or Democratic leadership.<br>
<br>
Trakon Mistrunner<br>
