<br>
You said the following:<br>
<br>
&quot;Deficits also effects the U.S. credit rating I believe. Therefore large international deals hinge on the deficits. International goods and services become even more expensive when the U.S. has a high deficit.&quot;<br>
<br>
That statement only makes sense if our national debt were high enough to trigger a credit downgrade.  It ain't even close.  The U.S. has the highest credit rating possible for sovereign governments.  We are nowhere near getting downgraded.  Your statement that large international deals hinge on deficits makes even less sense.  What international deals?  The credit ratings that are important in any commercial transaction are the corporate credit ratings of the parties involved.  Unless it is a rare transaction where the government is guaranteeing obligations of one of the parties, the credit rating of the government is irrelevant; what matters is the credit rating of the commercial entities.  International goods and services become even more expensive when the U.S. has a high deficit?  The only external factor that affects the prices of international goods and services is the exchange rate.  To the extent that a higher deficit moves the exchange rate, that would be true.<br>
<br>
